# Rope Fish: The Living Fossil of the Aquarium

The Rope Fish (*Erpetoichthys calabaricus*) is unlike anything else available in the freshwater aquarium hobby. It belongs to the family Polypteridae — an ancient lineage of actinopterygian (ray-finned) fish whose fossil record extends back 95+ million years, to the Late Cretaceous. Polypterids are so phylogenetically isolated from other fish that they retain anatomical structures not found in any other living ray-finned fish: rudimentary lungs capable of breathing air, thick ganoid scales resembling armour plating, a series of dorsal "finlets" rather than a continuous dorsal fin, and a distinctive fleshy pectoral fin base that more closely resembles the limb origin structures of tetrapods than standard fish fins.

In practical terms: a Rope Fish is an eel-shaped, air-breathing, armoured primitive fish that predates the K-Pg extinction event, will eat anything smaller than itself, and can escape from an aquarium through any gap wider than its head.

---

## Taxonomy and Evolutionary Significance

**Order Polypteriformes** — Contains two genera: *Erpetoichthys* (Rope Fish, one species) and *Polypterus* (Bichirs, 14 species). Together they form the earliest-diverging lineage of living ray-finned fishes.

**Evolutionary position:** Polypterids diverged from the main ray-finned fish lineage (Actinopterygii) before the radiation that produced all modern fish orders. They retain ancestral characters — including paired lungs — that other ray-finned fish lost over evolutionary time. The polypterid body plan represents what early freshwater fish looked like before the Devonian period.

**Closest evolutionary relatives:** Phylogenetically, Polypteriformes sit as the sister group to all other living ray-finned fish — a position that places them closer to tetrapod ancestors (amphibians, reptiles, birds, mammals) in some analytical frameworks than to perch, salmon, or goldfish.

The animal in your aquarium has remained morphologically similar to its Cretaceous ancestors. Most fish lineages it shares tanks with diverged from it 300+ million years ago.

