## The Escape Artist Problem

**Rope Fish are the most capable escape artists in the freshwater hobby.** This is not an exaggeration — Rope Fish escape from enclosures that other fish cannot exit, through mechanisms other fish would not attempt, at times that seem impossible.

**Escape mechanisms:**
- Gap detection: They probe every edge of the tank lid systematically and will find any gap wider than their head circumference
- Equipment openings: Filter inlet holes, airline tube openings, any penetration through the lid is a potential exit
- During feeding when the lid is removed — Common escape scenario
- At night — Most active escape attempts occur in darkness

**Rope Fish on land:** They can survive surprisingly long periods out of water if surfaces are moist — their primitive lung respiration combined with low activity rates allows them to breathe on land temporarily. They have been found alive hours after escaping. If found escaped, return to water immediately.

**Solutions:**
- Custom-fit lids with no gaps larger than 5mm
- Cover all equipment penetrations with fine mesh
- Use magnetic lid locks if fish are persistently probing openings
- Check behind and under tank furniture regularly — a missing Rope Fish may be behind equipment rather than on the floor

