## Feeding

**Rope Fish are obligate carnivores.** They will not eat plant matter. Their feeding is primarily olfactory-driven — they locate food by smell in low-visibility environments where vision is limited.

### Diet

**Live and frozen invertebrates:**
- **Earthworms** — Highly relished; nutritionally balanced. The ideal staple for Rope Fish. Long, worm-shaped prey is the natural analogue.
- **Bloodworms** (frozen or live) — Accepted readily
- **Blackworms** — Excellent; wriggling movement triggers predatory response
- **Prawns/shrimp** (frozen, shell-on) — Good protein; shell provides enrichment

**Live foods from Blackwater Aquatics:**
- **Baby Brine Shrimp** — Useful for juveniles; adults prefer larger prey. **[From Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**
- **Micro Worms** — For juveniles under 20cm. **[From Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**

**Live fish:** Do not feed live feeder fish — disease risk and behavioural habituation to live prey causes aggression toward tankmates. Not necessary; worms and invertebrates provide complete nutrition.

### Feeding Technique

Feed **after lights out**. Rope Fish are nocturnal — daytime feeding attempts are largely ignored. Use tongs or target-feed near the fish's resting spot with earthworms or bloodworm. Train them to a specific feeding zone.

**Hunger awareness:** Rope Fish can fast for 1–2 weeks without harm. Newly introduced fish may refuse food for 1–3 weeks while adjusting. Don't panic; offer food every 2–3 days and give time.

---

## Behaviour

**Nocturnal and crepuscular:** Inactive during daylight, emerging at dusk and after lights out for foraging activity.

**Slow, deliberate movement:** The serpentine body glides along substrate surfaces. Occasional fast bursts when startled or pursuing prey.

**Olfactory hunters:** They use the paired nasal openings (tubular, visible at the tip of the snout) to trail scent. Watch them "tracking" the scent trail of food placed in their tank.

**Group behaviour:** Rope Fish are not aggressive toward conspecifics and can be kept in groups in adequately sized tanks. They often pile together in shared hiding spots.

---

## Compatible Tankmates

**The key constraint: anything that fits in the Rope Fish's mouth will be eaten.** And their mouths are larger than they appear.

**Safe companions (large enough not to be eaten):**
- Large peaceful cichlids (Severums, Festivum Cichlids)
- Large Bichir species (close relatives; compatible)
- Large catfish species (*Synodontis* species)
- **[Oscar Fish](/species/oscar-fish)** — Similarly sized; may coexist in large tanks with monitoring
- Large Bristlenose/Common Pleco
- Large tetras (>8 cm body length)

**Unsafe:**
- Any fish under 10 cm
- Shrimp (eaten immediately)
- Small loaches
- Small corydoras
- Any elongated fish (perceived as worms; immediately predated)

